Peel and finely chop the @echalion shallots{2%large}, @garlic{2%cloves}. Clean the @chestnut mushrooms{1%punnet}(roughly chopped), preferably by wiping with #kitchen paper{} as this retains the flavour, but you can use water. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{2%sprigs}(finely chopped).

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} over a high heat. Add the mushrooms in small batches to make sure they go golden brown, then remove from the pan. Fry the @British smoked bacon lardons{2%handfuls} in the (now empty) pan, until it has started to crisp up. Then add the chopped shallot and garlic and cook for a few more ~{2-3%minutes}.

Return the mushrooms to the pan along with @water{200%ml} and a few grinds of @black pepper{a few grinds}. Allow to simmer over medium heat for ~{8-10%minutes} until thickened. Meanwhile, bring a #pot{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

In another frying pan, heat @oil{2%tbsp} on medium-high heat. When hot, add the @gnocchi{700%g}. Gently fry for ~{8%minutes} until it's crispy around the edges. Remove from the heat. Meanwhile, cut the @broccoli{1%head} up into small florets. Plunge into the pot of boiling water for ~{3%minutes}, then remove, drain and keep to the side.

Stir the @crème fraîche{1%small tub} into the mushroom sauce. Add the gnocchi and the broccoli to the sauce and give it all a good stir. Taste for seasoning and add more salt and pepper as you wish.

Divide the gnocchi between your #bowls{} and top with @parmesan cheese{4%tbsp}(grated) and the chopped parsley.

> We think that crispy pan-fried gnocchi with crème fraîche is not only super tasty but incredibly easy to make! The gnocchi has a crispy coating and a pillow-like centre, accompanied by 'meaty' chestnut mushrooms, tasty broccoli, cheese and flat leaf parsley. We think we've made our own delicacy with this twist on a classic Italian dish!